segments.text: Interview with Dr. Harrison.
Today's date is January 29th, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is a test.
So this is an interview with Dr. Harrison, a graduate of the first class of veterinary medicine in 1920.
Today is January 29th, 1981.
And I'd like to ask you first if we could start this interview by...

you agreeing to donate the tape to texas a m university will you agree to that yeah yeah okay thank you thank you very much could you tell us about your early years let's start with uh where and when you were born i was born right in brown up here on the hill really yeah in a two-story house and uh i've gone and see uh
I mean, you know, you get caught sometimes, you can't think of a thing.
I know, I know, I know.
Can you tell me about your parents?
Well, both of them are dead.
Yeah?
My father's dead and my mother's dead.
My mother died seven years after Papa died.
And what did they do?
They were medicine doctors.
Oh, they were medical doctors, both your mother and your dad?
No, no, no, no, no.
She was a housekeeper.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
She was strictly a housekeeper, and she had seven children.
No, five children.
Five children.
Five children.
That's a pretty good-sized family.
And your dad, your dad was a, your father was a medical.
Well, he graduated at University of Vanderbilt.
Oh, really?
Vanderbilt.
Okay.
And was he just a general practitioner?
Well, that's all they had here then.
That's all they need now.
It's good general practitioner fellows to go that when they call, they'll go.
But they won't do that now.
They want to meet them at the hospital.
And you get them in the hospital, and of course, it's easy to diagnose a case in the hospital, tears it out at the home.
But if you're well-practiced and well-versed, well, it doesn't make any difference, because outside of a blood test, you can tell pretty well what's going on with them.
Okay, okay.
Could you tell me about your early years growing up in Bryan?
Well, yeah, I could do it.
I went to high school right up here on the hill, right up here.
But it is now the high school now.
Let me see.
Where is the high school?
It's between here and college.
Yeah.
It's the high school now.
And it was built.
The architect was an A&M graduate.
And a small fellow about your size.
What were your favorite topics in high school, do you remember?
Topics, what do you mean?
Subjects.
What did you like to study then?
Oh, well, I wasn't interested in anything but athletics.
You were interested in football.
In football, yeah.
And football and baseball and basketball.
All three of those.
And track, I ran track two.
What type of races did you run?
I ran the 200 and 440 and a mile.
Why did you decide to go to Texas A&M?
I went to Texas A&M strictly to play football.
I always wanted to play football, and I always wanted to make a letter after A&M, and I did so.
By determination.
I was little.
I didn't weigh 135 pounds, 135, 36 pounds.
And that's all I weighed the whole time I was at A&M.
That is small for a football player.
But when I hit them, they knew they were hit.
Did you get a scholarship?
No, they didn't have any such thing as scholarships then.
We went to school because we wanted to go and wanted to go there.
We didn't know what scholarship was.
And don't know what it is now.
A lot of the boys at A&M College don't know what it is.
But they find out when they get out.
You were in the Corps of Cadets, of course, back then.
Oh, yeah.
I was Captain of the Sea Company and one of the honors that they had there at A&M in the Company C. Company C. I didn't have that until I went back to school my senior year.
I went back as a freshman.
What I mean by that, I went back without any designation at all.

But I was not very long or two or three days before I was made a captain of Company C. And I went to the president and told him that I didn't, the man that they had at Company C was a friend of mine and I didn't feel like that.
I said, take your job.
But he said, well... What did the president say to that?
Well, he said, well, you got it, didn't you?
I said, I did, but I didn't ask for it.
And he said, since you have it, well, then you're going to keep it.
And I said, all right, sir.
That's the way you feel about it.
That's all I mean.
I had to call.
I said, now, you call all the seniors together and have them talk to them and tell them why I took that job.
And he did.
He called them and had it right after lunch.
And I worked there 15 minutes.
Bazell was the president of the school and he was from Navasola.
And he was followed by a man from Navasola.
What did you think of Bazell?
Oh, I liked him very well.
But Bill was a good man.
He went from Texas, he was here about 11, 12 years, and then he went up to Oklahoma.
He saw his, you know, when a man's at a place that's certainly time, it's time for him to move on.
He ought to.
What he does not, he ought to move on.
And so I went around and saw him, talked to him.
And he was tickled to death before I came by.
They all called me Chick.
I had a nickname and they followed me from here.
Why did they call you Chick?
Well, it's a long story.
The main thing was that my father took my brother and I to Houston.
Got there where we had breakfast, actually, because we left on a four o'clock train.
And we went right across the street to the old batter's hotel and had dinner, had supper, or had breakfast.
I get it after a while.
And so they asked me what I wanted.
I said, well, what I want is chicken.
He said, they don't serve chicken for breakfast yet.
I said, I can't have that.
I said, you asked me what I wanted, and that's what I want.
But I can't get it, so I'll take some mayonnaise.
He said, it'll be fine.
You got that, I know.
And he said, yep, you got that.
And so from then on, I was called Chick.
Oh, really?
And then on I was called to, my father went to school at A&M too.
Yeah, he went there one year.
And he graduated, he didn't graduate from that, but he graduated in medicine in 91.
And he began practicing, he got married, and mother, she was, her first husband was a conductor.
He was a conductor on a train.
And he was killed by a Mexican.
By a Mexican that got on a train, he told me he didn't have a ticket.
And he said, well, if you don't have a ticket, you can't go.
He said, I'm going.
He said, no, you're not either.
And so he just pulled out a gun and shot him and killed him.
Well, that's terrible.
And so I don't know what kind of make much difference or what.
whether they did anything to the Michigan Nine, I guess they did, because they were looking for something, a good bed to sleep in, and three meals a day is what they were looking for.
What about your interests besides sports at A&M?
Were you particularly interested in any professors or any subjects?
Oh, I got along with all of them.
I got along with all of them.
I knew them all.
except the new ones that came in there.
I can, you want the names of the professors?
Well, if you remember them.
Oh, I remember them.
Oh, well, okay.
One of them was a little Jew, and he was graduating, he taught from college.
And so he, when
We all finished.
Four years.
Eighteen was in the class.
They started out and only four graduated.
And they either dropped out or they quit or something.
But anyhow, there were four.
And those four were a fellow by the name of Murray and a fellow by the name of Murray and... Hall and Rosenberg.
Roseburg and Hall and- Hall and Murray.
Well, Fritz Murray was one of- Right.
Yeah, four of them.
Four graduates.
And they all lived but me.
Murray used to be at- was a- died at Taylor.
Can you tell me about these classmates of yours?
What kind of people they were?
We don't have much information on them.
We have their pictures, and that's about all.
Well, Merle got that phone.
Well, yeah, Merle, he was from, he was a foreigner.
He came here to go to school.
Was he from England or Germany?
No, he wasn't from any place.
He was from...
What was he now?
He was about 40 years old when he came there.
Oh, really?
I didn't know that.
Oh, yeah.
He talked funny and he used to take care of the children for the professors when they wanted to go out at night.
They'd call them up and see if he was going to be busy that night.
If he wasn't, well, they'd harm.
And they would harm
to stay there with the children and look after the children until 11 o'clock or 12 o'clock when they came back.
That's the way he did that all four years when he was a senior on now.
What kind of person was Murray?
He was a nice fella.
He got along with everybody.
Very nice fella.
He would
Oh, well, he was very nice.
All I can say, I'm not much on describing a man, saying what a man can do.
What about Joe Hall?
Well, old Joe, he was from Carthage, Texas.
He's dead.
As I said, they're all dead now.
And he was very good.
I don't think he had a book while he was at A&M.
He went to class and paid attention in class.
And he was able to graduate without buying a book.
Now he bought a book and used library one.
I don't know which.
But anyhow, he graduated.
You thought he was very smart then?
Oh yeah, he was smart.
Joe was very smart.
And he had a sister that was going to, while he was going to A&M, his sister was going to CIA.
That's up above Dallas.
And what about Rosenberg?
Rosenberg was, he was, he was a father was, went broke during the Depression, the first Depression we had, you know.
And he was a cotton buyer.
He dealt in cotton and he lost all his money in the cotton.
He bought cotton and bought futures.
And, you know, you buy futures.
Sure.
They go down, well if you don't have money to pay them, they don't care a thing about it.
They just sell it and get what they have in it.
And so he sold, his father was a very prominent man in the place he lived.
What kind of student was Rosenberg?
He was a very good student.
All four of them were very good students.
They all graduated at A&M and I guess that's about all I can say about him.
He was a very good student, all I can say.
Being in the very first class of the vet school,
Did you think that there were any special pressures on you or any special ideas about what veterinarians were supposed to be because you were the first class?
Do you think that the professors treated you any differently?
No, they didn't.
They treated me just the same as everyone else.
Why did you decide to go to vet school?
because they didn't have any, that was before they had to, you know, classes set aside for medicine.
And so I decided that since they didn't have any out there, I wanted to go to A&M.
And since they didn't have any out there, well, I went ahead and took back medicine because it was the only thing that I knew that I could take that,
that would help me in a few years.
And it did help a whole lot.
And then later on you decided to go to medical school.
Four years later I decided to go to medical school.
In between time I worked for the state.
I was with the Livestock Sanitary Commission in the wheat building.
It's torn down now and I haven't been back there since then.
And what did you do?
I went all over Texas.
I had a regular pass, I'd buy the tickets myself, and buy a book of tickets.
And when I, the state would furnish them.
And I'd go out, I told the head, the state veterinarian to keep me out of the office all he could.
I didn't want to, since I was on a salary and was being paid by the month, that I was, I could keep my money in the bank a lot easier than I could if I had it in my pocket.
And so you traveled around Texas, and what did you do?
I went out and was like a veterinarian.
Went out and saw the animals, a bunch of them.
I saw them and saw if they were dying from an infectious disease.
Well, if I could get the vaccine, I'd get it and vaccinate the cattle for them.
I see.
The first job I had, I was...
It was set down in the town, it was down in Brackettville.
And I stayed there three months.
And I slept in a courthouse and took a bath in a jail.
Really?
Because there wasn't any hotel?
There was a hotel, a 32-story old building that a color woman had for a hotel, but that's about all.
But they had a post there.
And the Army had a post there.
And I heard that they were going to take the horses out on a trip.
And I said, no, you're not.
I went over there, and he said, yeah.
I said, well, we're going to take the horses on a trip.
And I said, you can't move those horses now.
You can ride them around town all you want to.
But as far as moving them and taking them out of the city limits, you're not going to do it.
Because if there's any such thing as infectious disease, that's bad, and they were right in the midst of an anthrax epidemic.
You know how anthrax works.
He didn't like it very much, but I told him, I said, he said, how are you going to stop me?
I said, well, if you just try it, I'll show you.
Because it won't take me 15 minutes to get the telephone and call Austin.
And from Austin, I can get a man here in 24 hours that will stop you.
And that won't
give the permission for you to take the horses out of the stable and take them out in the field.
So were those horses eventually destroyed then?
We didn't do anything at all.
We just vaccinated them and that's it.
I see.
Were there times
During these four years when you would have to destroy a herd?
No, no, no one did have to destroy a herd.
Good.
No one did have to destroy a herd.
A herd meant most of cattle.
Yeah.
No, no, no one did have to destroy a herd.
I had to interview the horses I had to.
Excuse me.
Okay.
Besides going around the state and vaccinating cattle and horses during those four years when you were a veterinarian for the state, did you do other things?
No, no.
I didn't do other things.
I didn't have time to do other things.
But I mean that was your main job.
That was the main function of that job.
The main job.
They called into the state at Fort Worth and talked to the state veterinarian and
he would get a job, whatever he wanted me to do.
I wasn't scared.
I was raised with horses and cows, and I wasn't scared of them.
Now most of the men that were there, well, they said they wasn't, but they were.
They were scared, and it was pretty hard to get them to go.
But I always wanted to go.
And so it wasn't going to be a bit in the world.
Why did you decide to get out of veterinary medicine then and go to medical school?
Why did you decide that changed in your life?
Well, I always wanted to be a doctor.
Why was that?
Because my father would.
But I wanted to go to A&M.
And when I got through A&M, I had to have the money to go to medical school, so I had to work four years and make the money and save it.
And at the end of four years, well, I had enough.
And what I saved put me through the medical school.
I see.
Because I didn't spend anything for foolishness.
And where'd you go to medical school?
I went to Dallas to Baylor.
Why'd you decide on Baylor?
Well, it was, I thought, one of the best schools in medicine.
And I wrote other places.
I was accepted, but I didn't go.
I wrote back and told them I decided to go to Baylor.
And Baylor was close to Fort Worth, and Fort Worth was where my home was.
That wasn't my home, right here.
But I lived there in Fort Worth, so I knew Dallas pretty well.
And so when I went to medical school,
had to do was look around and find a place to live.
And I went to the furniture people here in town and they were very nice to me and gave me a letter to the manager of one of the places I could purchase the desired furniture that I wanted.
I was all fixed up.
Okay.
Now, do you remember in 1916 when you were admitted to the vet school, do you remember what the entrance requirements were like or anything like that?
Were you interviewed by professors here?
No, no.
We didn't have any interviews.
They all knew me and it wasn't necessarily much.
They knew more about me than I did about the school.
But they didn't have any interviews at all.
I don't know whether they have them any now or not.
Well they did for a while, but they did for a while in the 30s and 40s and 50s, but now there's so many people that want to go to vet school that they don't interview anymore.
When you were in the Corps, remember when you were in the Corps, we had a housing shortage.
at Texas A&M during the 19-teens.
Were you living in a tent then?
Do you remember?
Did you live at home?
Oh, I remember tents.
Do you remember the tents?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I remember them very well.
They was all lined up on one side of Main Street, what we called Main Street, the street that led from the
from the station up to school was the main road.
Then they had the tents lined up there.
Did you live in a tent or did you live at home?
No, I stayed out in Colorado four years.
I lived in one of the halls.
Leggett Hall and Milner Hall and Foster Hall.
I bet you living in the tents was a pretty rough life.
Well it wasn't so rough.
It was warm and we burnt wood then.
Right, yeah.
And the boys would, they would use the three to the room and they had
large tents.
I believe they were fourteen to twenty, I believe they were, but they were just one room.
And three lived in those tents.
Oh yeah, I was here very well, but living here made it, made them close to me to get to.
made a lot easier probably.
Well, it did.
I knew it.
I knew the school and knew the professors.
Right.
Did your dad know the professors over there pretty well because he was a medical doctor and had contact?
Oh yes, he knew the main ones.
He knew Dean Francis, the head of school, and Mark Stella was
was the chief medical man.
He taught us the diseases of ambulance and he also had the, I guess you'd call it the dispensary.
So he had all the boys.
Well, let's talk about those teachers who were the ones who really established the vet school back in the 19-teens.
Can you tell us about Mark Francis?
Well, Mark Francis came there from Ohio State.
He graduated from Ohio State, and he came directly from Ohio State to A&M, and they didn't have vet medicine at A&M.
I think that was one reason why they developed the School of Veterinary Medicine.
So he taught anatomy.
What kind of teacher was he?
Oh, he was a very good teacher.
Very good teacher.
Was he a hard or an easy grader?
Do you remember?
I just don't know.
I can't answer that question very well.
He wasn't hard on the students or anything like that, but he'd take it in the foosters.
And if they had any foosters about them, he'd pick them out and tell them to either quit the foosters or leave school.
Those that couldn't take it were left and those that could take it were quit it and they stayed.
As long as they was able to pass the work.
Now did you like him as a person?
Did you think he was a nice person to know?
Well, he was a man that
Now we're talking about the dean.
He was a man that was very likeable to the boys.
He would know them and how to do it and something like that and then go on.
He wouldn't stop and talk and so forth and so on.
And he was hard of hearing and that's another reason why he was
